In[2]:
import statsmodels.tsa.stattools as ts
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

MA(q) process

First decide a MA(q) process and simulate it using the statsmodels
Let's take $X_t = Z_t + 0.7Z_{t-1} + 0.5Z_{t-2}$
Implies this is MA(2) process ($X_t = Z_t + \beta_1Z_{t-1} + \beta_2Z_{t-2}$, with $\beta_1=0.7$ and $\beta_2=0.5$)

ARMA simulator in statsmodels takes arguments ar and ma
The conventions of the arma_generate function require that we specify a 1 for the zero-lag of the AR and MA parameters and that the AR parameters be negated.
For example: if ARMA process is given by Then ar = $[1,-\phi_1,-\phi_2,-\phi_3,....]$
and ma = $[1,\theta_1,\theta_2,\theta_3,....]$
In[18]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa import arima_process
ma_params = [1,0.7,0.5]
ar_params = [1]
x = arima_process.arma_generate_sample(ar=ar_params,ma=ma_params,nsample=100)
plt.figure(figsize=(24,6))
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
plt.title("MA(2) Process")
plt.plot(x)

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
acovf_x = ts.acovf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlag=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acovf_x)),height=acovf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.title("Auto Covariance of MA(2) process")

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
acorf_x = ts.acf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acorf_x)),height=acorf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Correlation of MA(2) process")
#plt.plot(x)
plt.show()

We know that:
A moving average process of order q has an ACF that cuts off after q lags.
And we see that ACF for MA(2) process cuts off after 2 lags.

print(acorf_x[0:3])

[1.         0.59676223 0.28975416]

We can also solve this using statsmodels library
statsmodels.tsa.arima.model.ARIMA(endog,order=(p,d,q))
endog has the time series
p,q = (0,0,2) for the above MA(2) process

In[36]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
mod = ARIMA(endog=x, order=(0,0,2))
res = mod.fit()
print('Model Specification : ',res.specification,'\n')
print('Autoregression Coefficients : ',res.polynomial_ar,'\n')
print('Moving Average Coefficients : ',res.polynomial_ma,'\n')
print('AIC (Akaike information criterion) : ',res.aic,'\n')

AR(p) process

First decide a AR(p) process and simulate it using the statsmodels
Let's take $X_t = Z_t + 0.6X_{t-1} + 0.3X_{t-2}$
Implies this is AR(2) process ($X_t = Z_t + \phi_1X_{t-1} + \phi_2X_{t-2}$, with $\phi_1=0.6$ and $\phi_2=0.3$)

In[78]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa import arima_process
ar_params = [1,-0.6,-0.3]
ma_params = [1]
x = arima_process.arma_generate_sample(ar=ar_params,ma=ma_params,nsample=100)
plt.figure(figsize=(24,6))
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
plt.title("AR(2) Process")
plt.plot(x)

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
acorf_x = ts.acf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acorf_x)),height=acorf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Correlation of AR(2) process")

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
apcorf_x = ts.pacf(x,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(apcorf_x)),height=apcorf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Partial Auto Correlation of AR(2) process")

#plt.plot(x)
plt.show()

We know that:
An autoregressive process of order p, an AR(p), has a PACF that cuts off after p lags.
And we see that PACF for AR(2) process cuts off after 2 lags.

r1 = acorf_x[1]
r2 = acorf_x[2]
A = np.array([[1, r1], [r1, 1]])
b = np.array([r1, r2])
x = np.linalg.solve(A, b)
print(x)
print('which is close to actual values [0.6,0.3]')

[0.61820898 0.2861031 ]
which is close to actual values [0.6,0.3]

We can also solve this using statsmodels library

endog has the time series
p,q = (2,0,0) for the above AR(2) process
